               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "### Prerequisites\n\nThis text will continue to delve deeper into negative numbers, as presented in the previous text (<htcite0>). Therefore, we recommend that you study it before proceeding.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b8c8840f-0631-420d-b5b3-7ebbebdb9625",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Integers",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nWhen studying the need for negative numbers through images reflected in mirrors or on water surfaces, we observe that on both sides we have the same numbers, but we use the negative sign (−) to identify the sides (**Graph 1**).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b8c8840f-0631-420d-b5b3-7ebbebdb9625",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Integers",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><svg width=\"500\" height=\"100\"  fill=\"none\" stroke=\"black\"> <defs> <marker id=\"arrow\" viewBox=\"0 0 10 10\" refX=\"5\" refY=\"5\" markerWidth=\"6\" markerHeight=\"6\" orient=\"auto-start-reverse\"> <path d=\"M 0 0 L 10 5 L 0 10 z\" /></marker> </defs> <line x1=\"8\" y1=\"75\" x2=\"490\" y2=\"75\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" marker-start=\"url(#arrow)\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <line x1=\"50\" y1=\"75\" x2=\"50\" y2=\"85\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" /> <line x1=\"90\" y1=\"75\" x2=\"90\" y2=\"85\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" /> <line x1=\"130\" y1=\"75\" x2=\"130\" y2=\"85\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" /> <line x1=\"170\" y1=\"75\" x2=\"170\" y2=\"85\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" /> <line x1=\"210\" y1=\"75\" x2=\"210\" y2=\"85\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" /> <line x1=\"250\" y1=\"75\" x2=\"250\" y2=\"85\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" /> <line x1=\"290\" y1=\"75\" x2=\"290\" y2=\"85\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" /> <line x1=\"330\" y1=\"75\" x2=\"330\" y2=\"85\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" /> <line x1=\"370\" y1=\"75\" x2=\"370\" y2=\"85\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" /> <line x1=\"410\" y1=\"75\" x2=\"410\" y2=\"85\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" /> <line x1=\"450\" y1=\"75\" x2=\"450\" y2=\"85\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" /> <circle cx=\"50\" cy=\"25\" r=\"7\" fill=\"#00FF00\"></circle> <circle cx=\"450\" cy=\"25\" r=\"7\" fill=\"#00FF00\"></circle> <line x1=\"250\" y1=\"75\" x2=\"250\" y2=\"5\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"7\" /> <text x=\"40\" y=\"99\" font-size=\"1.5em\">- 5</text> <text x=\"80\" y=\"99\" font-size=\"1.5em\">- 4</text> <text x=\"120\" y=\"99\" font-size=\"1.5em\">- 3</text> <text x=\"160\" y=\"99\" font-size=\"1.5em\">- 2</text> <text x=\"200\" y=\"99\" font-size=\"1.5em\">- 1</text> <text x=\"245\" y=\"99\" font-size=\"1.5em\">0</text> <text x=\"285\" y=\"99\" font-size=\"1.5em\">1</text> <text x=\"325\" y=\"99\" font-size=\"1.5em\">2</text> <text x=\"365\" y=\"99\" font-size=\"1.5em\">3</text> <text x=\"405\" y=\"99\" font-size=\"1.5em\">4</text> <text x=\"445\" y=\"99\" font-size=\"1.5em\">5</text> </svg></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Graph 1</b>: Representation of a mirror in the center, reflecting, on the left, an image that is to its right, with integers measuring the distance.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: How to measure?</b><br /><br />When looking at <b>Graph 1</b>, we see that the reflected image on the left is at the same distance as the original image on the right.<br /><br />The major difference between the sides is that, on the left side, we add the negative sign to indicate that the direction is different.<br /><br />What is the distance from the image on the left to the object on the right?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_distance",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Distance\n\nWhen working with distances in *History Tracers*, we learned that to calculate it, we subtract the initial position from the final position (<htcite0>). Applying this concept in **Graph 1**, on the right, we see that the distance at which an object was placed from the mirror is equal to 5:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "73cb1665-6b60-4725-a231-2aff976e7e6d",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Returning",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p style=\"text-align=center\"><center>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;5<br />-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;0<br />____________<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;5</center></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 1</b>: Distance of the object from the origin.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "There is something we must draw attention to in both **Graph 1** and **Calculation 1**. Notice that both use the minus sign (−). In one case, it is used to indicate direction; in the other, to perform a mathematical operation.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: What do they have in common?</b><br /><br />Can you identify anything in common between the graph and the mathematical operation?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_continuing",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Subtraction is a Sum\n\nAs we saw initially, subtraction can be understood as going back along a path we have traveled (<htcite0>), meaning we reverse the direction. Similarly, negative numbers on the graph also indicate that we are going in an opposite direction. Thus, the sign on both the graph and in the operation represents the same idea of going in an opposite direction.\n\nAnother fact we can recall from previous texts is that, as we moved among numbers, we always considered that we were walking by adding values to the previous number (<htcite1>).\n\nGiven this scenario, we can treat subtraction in a more general way.\n\n#### Going Back a Bit Further\n\nSuppose that, instead of measuring the distance from the object on the right to the mirror, we want to measure the distance from it to its image on the left. Applying subtraction, we would have:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "73cb1665-6b60-4725-a231-2aff976e7e6d",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Returning",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "0713ca05-8889-427b-802e-f2d31f045c09",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Walking Among Numbers",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p style=\"text-align=center\"><center>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;5<br />-&nbsp;- 5<br />____________</center></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 2</b>: Distance from the object to its image.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "In **Calculation 2**, we would like to draw attention to the fact that, when writing the subtraction, on the second line we have two negative signs. This is the first time this has occurred in all the texts of the *First Steps* section of History Tracers. With this, we can conclude that this is not the way we normally write it. In order to convert these two signs into a single one, as we have done so far, we will recall another graph used in the previous text (<htcite0>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b8c8840f-0631-420d-b5b3-7ebbebdb9625",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Integers",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><svg width=\"500\" height=\"100\"  fill=\"none\" stroke=\"black\"> <defs> <marker id=\"arrow\" viewBox=\"0 0 10 10\" refX=\"5\" refY=\"5\" markerWidth=\"6\" markerHeight=\"6\" orient=\"auto-start-reverse\"> <path d=\"M 0 0 L 10 5 L 0 10 z\" /></marker> </defs> <line x1=\"8\" y1=\"75\" x2=\"490\" y2=\"75\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" marker-start=\"url(#arrow)\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <line x1=\"50\" y1=\"75\" x2=\"50\" y2=\"85\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" /> <line x1=\"90\" y1=\"75\" x2=\"90\" y2=\"85\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" /> <line x1=\"130\" y1=\"75\" x2=\"130\" y2=\"85\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" /> <line x1=\"170\" y1=\"75\" x2=\"170\" y2=\"85\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" /> <line x1=\"210\" y1=\"75\" x2=\"210\" y2=\"85\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" /> <line x1=\"250\" y1=\"75\" x2=\"250\" y2=\"85\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" /> <line x1=\"290\" y1=\"75\" x2=\"290\" y2=\"85\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" /> <line x1=\"330\" y1=\"75\" x2=\"330\" y2=\"85\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" /> <line x1=\"370\" y1=\"75\" x2=\"370\" y2=\"85\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" /> <line x1=\"410\" y1=\"75\" x2=\"410\" y2=\"85\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" /> <line x1=\"450\" y1=\"75\" x2=\"450\" y2=\"85\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" /> <circle cx=\"50\" cy=\"25\" r=\"7\" fill=\"#00FF00\"></circle> <circle cx=\"450\" cy=\"25\" r=\"7\" fill=\"#00FF00\"></circle> <line x1=\"250\" y1=\"75\" x2=\"250\" y2=\"5\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"7\" /> <text x=\"45\" y=\"99\" font-size=\"1.5em\">5</text> <text x=\"85\" y=\"99\" font-size=\"1.5em\">4</text> <text x=\"125\" y=\"99\" font-size=\"1.5em\">3</text> <text x=\"165\" y=\"99\" font-size=\"1.5em\">2</text> <text x=\"205\" y=\"99\" font-size=\"1.5em\">1</text> <text x=\"245\" y=\"99\" font-size=\"1.5em\">0</text> <text x=\"285\" y=\"99\" font-size=\"1.5em\">1</text> <text x=\"325\" y=\"99\" font-size=\"1.5em\">2</text> <text x=\"365\" y=\"99\" font-size=\"1.5em\">3</text> <text x=\"405\" y=\"99\" font-size=\"1.5em\">4</text> <text x=\"445\" y=\"99\" font-size=\"1.5em\">5</text> </svg></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Graph 2</b>: Representation of a mirror in the center reflecting, on the left, an image of an object that is on its right, with numbers measuring the distance.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Combining Signs\n\nIn **Graph 2**, we removed the negative sign so we could better visualize the steps we are taking. If we were to calculate the distance from the image on the left to the mirror, and then add it to the result obtained in **Calculation 1**, we would have as a result:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mn>5</mn> <mo>-</mo> <mn>0</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mn>5</mn> </math></center></p> <p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mn>5</mn> <mo>-</mo> <mn>0</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mn>5</mn> </math></center></p> <p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mn>5</mn> <mo>+</mo> <mn>5</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mn>10</mn> </math></center></p> <p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 3</b>: Measurement of the distance to the right, to the left, and the sum of the total distance.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "To avoid any doubt, let's explain **Calculation 3** step by step:\n- **Line 1**: We repeat **Calculation 1**, which measures the distance from the object on the right to the center;\n- **Line 2**: Using **Graph 2**, we calculate the distance value from the image on the left to the mirror in the center;\n- **Line 3**: We add the results from **Lines 1 and 2**.\n\nFrom these results, we can conclude that when we have two negative signs in subtraction, as in **Calculation 2**, we start adding instead of subtracting, indicating that we are going in the same direction. That is, **Calculation 2** becomes:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p style=\"text-align=center\"><center>&nbsp;1&nbsp;&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;5<br />+&nbsp;&nbsp;5<br />____________<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;10</center></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 4</b>: Distance between object and image.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_indigenous",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### An Indigenous Perspective\n\nTo further illustrate this transition between the sides, and the fact that we still maintain the same nature, let's look at **Table 1** from Copán, Honduras (*Abya Yala*):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "1e007481-9bd3-4a09-ad4d-6e812fe79641",
                     "text": "Instituto Hondureño de Antropologia e Historia",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table class=\"tawapukllay\" id=\"tblStelaC\"><tr><th>West Side</th><th>East Side</th></tr> <tr id=\"tr0\"><td><img id=\"CWest\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('CWest', '0%');\" src=\"images/Copan/CopanStelaCBeard.jpg\" style=\"width:50%\" /></td><td><img id=\"CEast\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('CEast', '0%');\" src=\"images/Copan/CopanStelaC.jpg\" style=\"width:50%\" /></td></tr> </table></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Table 1</b>: Two sides of Stela C from Copán (<htcite0>). Photos taken on <htdate1>, during a visit to the site.</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "1e007481-9bd3-4a09-ad4d-6e812fe79641",
                     "text": "Instituto Hondureño de Antropologia e Historia",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2024",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2015",
                     "month": "7",
                     "day": "30"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "The table contains two images of the same *ajaw* (rei), Waxaklajuun Ubaah K'awiil. These images are from Stela C, which depicts the ajaw (king) without a beard on the side facing east — the side where the Sun appears in the morning — and with a beard on the side facing west — where the Sun “disappears” and dusk begins. Comparing the two images with the number line, we can observe:\n- Stela C shows the passage of time, with dawn facing the positive side of numbers and dusk facing the negative side;\n- As the count of time always increases, the stela shows time passing in a direction opposite to that in which we write larger and smaller numbers;\n- In the same way that the images on the stela are of the same person — one with a beard and one without — the numbers on both sides of zero are integers and, instead of the beard, we use the negative sign to differentiate what is smaller from what is larger.\n\nThere is still much to extract from these observations; for now, we will focus only on the fact that, while the indigenous people used the beard to differentiate what was the greater time, we use a sign to indicate a lesser value. The general idea is the same, although we use different “signs” to indicate directions.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_conclusion",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Conclusion\n\nIn this text, we learned how to measure distances in images and, consequently, how to subtract numbers with different signs. Furthermore, through indigenous cultures, we learned that the use of signs to indicate transitions has been observed by different populations throughout history.\n\nFinally, we saw that we have not exhausted the study of negative numbers in this text, which is why we will continue exploring the subject in the next one.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      }
   ],
   "exercise_v2": [
      {
         "question": "When measuring a distance from the right side to the left side, do we divide the numbers?",
         "yesNoAnswer": "No",
         "additionalInfo": "Distance is measured in the same way, whether going to zero or continuing in another direction. We just need to keep in mind that when we cross zero, we will begin adding the values, instead of continuing to subtract."
      },
      {
         "question": "Can we understand addition and subtraction as similar operations?",
         "yesNoAnswer": "Yes",
         "additionalInfo": "We can understand subtraction as the addition of two numbers with different signs — and, therefore, different directions. When one of the numbers is negative and we want to subtract from it, we invert its sign (making it positive) and explicitly perform an addition."
      }
   ],
   "game_v2": null,
   "date_time": null
}
